"Our Classic Bobtail has proven so popular due to its concealable profile that we decided to bring you something even more concealable -- the Concealed Carry Officer. This model is built as a classic CCO, with a Commander slide on top of an Officer frame. This combination provides the control and reliability of the Commander with the easy concealment of the Officer frame. With the proven stopping power of the .45 ACP in the two provided 7 round flush base magazines, you won’t feel under-gunned.

To make it more comfortable and make it disappear even easier while carrying concealed, we bobbed the back of the mainspring housing. To reduce the overall weight, the frame and mainspring housing are made from anodized aluminum. To help control recoil, we included an undercut trigger guard and our new “Chain Link” pattern on the front strap and mainspring housing. The slide and small parts are coated in the same “Duty” finish that we use on the Valor. Like all of our night-sight models, you will find dual colored Tritium lamps for faster low-light target acquisition and a white target ring on the front to aid in front sight concentration. title: For Sale:  WWII Remington 1903A3 Bolt Action Rifle With New Barrel
location: Aiken, Williston, Barnwell, Columbia, South Carolina
postcontent:
I bought this grand old workhorse Remington 1903A3 when it had a bad barrel.  I purchased a new-old-stock Remington 1903A3 barrel, and hired a gunsmith to rebarrel it.  His functional checkout included firing three rounds, and that is all that has been shot through this jewel.
The black parkerized receiver and bolt indicates that this rifle was lend-leased to Greece, post WWII.  It was imported back into the USA, and now into the hands of a collector who cannot shoot high-power bolt action rifles any more, for health reasons.  It shoots the same round as the M1 Garand, which is called M2 ball, in .30-06 caliber.

The 1903A3 is basically a Springfield design 1903 rifle, but with improved sighting system.  The rear sight was moved to the rear of the receiver to increase sight radius.  The rear sight was also redesigned to give more reliable and quick windage adjustment, and easier distance settings.

The serial number on the bolt's handle matches the receiver's serial number.  The Remington barrel that is now installed is stamped Dec. 43, which is the same year the receiver was made.

An excellent shooter with the highly regarded USGI two-groove barrel.  The "scant" stock is in excellent condition, and was carefully cleaned and treated with tung oil (correct for this rifle).

Web sling included.

title: For Sale:  DEAL PENDING-------Colt 1902 Military Semi-Auto Pistol WWI
location: Aiken, Williston, Barnwell, Columbia, South Carolina
postcontent:
A highly collectable Colt Model 1902 Military, chambered in .38ACP (.38 Auto), with 6" barrel.  The predecessor to the Colt Model 1911, with many of the same features, but uniquely different.

Colt built just a few hundred of these each year.  This particular pistol was built in 1912, and was carried by a US Army officer during WWI.  Appears to have been stored inside a leather holster for some time after the war, because it has minor pitting on the slide, and has been [lovingly] reblued, which was the original  factory finish.  All original markings remain easily readable.
A bit of pitting is still visible on the slide, but does not significantly take away from the beauty of this historic piece.  The bore is quite nice, and matches the rest of the pistol.  The original magazine is also included.  
The front and rear sights are designed for very fine aiming, and reminiscent of the early 20th century .22 rifles.  Test fired for function, and is quite accurate, even with vintage ammo.

I also have 150 rounds of newly made ammunition, and will pass them along to the new owner for free, FTF.

These pistols in good condition with original finish are selling for $2,500-$3,000, so I am offering this one at less than 1/2 of the low end value, due to the reblued finish.  I am sure you will agree that the job was done exceptionally well.

title: For Sale:  Springfield 03A3 and M1905 Bayonet
location: West of Berthoud, CO, Fort Collins, Colorado
postcontent:
1903 A3 Springfield Rifle made by Smith Corona and M1905 Bayonet.
The rifle was purchased 10/16/81 from Federal Ordnance and never fired by me.  It has a Smith Corona receiver with a serial number preceded by a “C” indicating there is also a Remington out there with the same serial number without the “C.”  The barrel is a Remington Arms four groove marked 8-44.  Federal Ordnance literature stated that this lot of O3-A3's had been discovered in a National Guard armory, purchased by them, checked out and offered for sale.

The bayonet is a never issued M1905 that is parkerized and unsharpened.  It has two chips in the blade and its serial number indicates it was made in 1907 and is so stamped.  The nicks would go away with sharpening.  A bit of history:  The first M1905 came out in 1906 and produced to 1922 and all of them still in inventory were parkerized in 1919.  A shiny one is reportedly rare.  Many were cut down in WWII as it made the rifle and bayonet difficult to wield in a jungle due to overall length.  A good looking scabbard is also rare as they were belt worn and the leather tips were worn down.  I've seen the bayonet offered by itself for $400.

Included is a correct M1910 scabbard for the bayonet in rough condition, an ammunition belt with 125 rounds of 30-06 ball on stripper clips, cleaning kit in butt and a correct original manual for the firearm.  Federal Ordnance literature at time of purchase states that the rifle is “as issued” complete and in perfect working order having been checked, test fired and head spaced by its armorers.  Very nice looking rifle with correct additions that will make all the other guys at the range jealous.

I'd like to sell this to a fellow Coloradoan or someone in a contiguous state to avoid the hassle and costs of going through a dealer.  Since it is over 50 years old it is eligible for sale direct to a C&R FFL holder if they meet my terms.

Democrats control the Colorado legislature and governorship with pending laws to make all private party sales illegal unless through a dealer.  The cost to purchase and time delay in taking possession will only go up should (and probably will) occur.  Don't hesitate.

title: For Sale:  Czech VZ 58
postcontent:
Like new CZ 58, zeroed and fired only 60 rounds. Milled Receiver. Comes with 6, 30 round magazines! Similar to an AK 47 in its looks only, very fine rifle thats extremely accurate. $750 cash.

Here is a description and a generic picture i lifted from the internet, my rifle is identical to it...

Sa vz. 58 Comparison to AK-47 Type Rifle with Stamped Receiver
All vz. 58 rifles possess a milled receiver; the vast majority of AK-47s are stamped.
Even with the milled receiver it is almost one pound lighter than a stamped AK-47.
CNC machining on a vz. 58 receiver takes 2 1/2 hours; a stamped AK-47 receiver takes seconds to produce.
The bolt of the vz. 58 stays open after the last round in the magazine has been fired.
The vz. 58 can be reloaded with stripper clips while the magazine is inserted in the rifle.
The vz. 58 has a more natural point of aim and is faster handling.
The safety is more ergonomic making a faster first shot possible with the vz. 58.
The ejection port is HUGE. There is no chance of an empty case getting stuck in the action of the vz. 58.
The vz. 58 gas piston can be removed or exchanged without tools.
The alloy magazine of the vz. 58 is half the weight of the steel AK-47 magazine. (.42 lb. vs. .84 lb.)
The vz. 58 is striker fired unlike the hammer fired AK-47. This reduces the number of parts and possible points of failure.
By the end of the 1950s, the Sa vz. 58 military issued assault rifle had obtained the impressive combination of weight and length (6.42 lbs and 33.30 inches for fixed stock) to make this rifle the elite among military issued assault rifles of its class.
